<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="19" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="19">
Three 
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" family="Gnomoniaceae" genus="Gnomoniopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Gnomoniopsis" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Gnomoniopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species have been discovered from the host genus 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Castanea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Castanea" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Castanea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. They share similar conidial dimension (6.0-9.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2.2-3.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. M. Tian &amp; N. Jiang" authorityYear="2020" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Gnomoniaceae" genus="Gnomoniopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Gnomoniopsis chinensis" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="chinensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Gnomoniopsis chinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
vs. 5.0-8.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2.0-3.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
in 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. daii" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="daii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">G. daii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
vs. 6.0-9.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2.0-4.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
in 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. smithogilvyi" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="smithogilvyi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">G. smithogilvyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3767/003158512X652633" author="Crous, PW" journalOrPublisher="Persoonia" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" pagination="138 - 182" refId="B5" refString="Crous, PW, Summerell, BA, Shivas, RG, Burgess, TI, Decock, CA, Dreyer, LL, Granke, LL, Guest, DI, Hardy, GESTJ, Hausbeck, MK, Hueberli, D, Jung, T, Koukol, O, Lennox, CL, Liew, ECY, Lombard, L, McTaggart, AR, Pryke, JS, Roets, F, Saude, C, Shuttleworth, LA, Stukely, MJC, Vanky, K, Webster, BJ, Windstam, ST, Groenewald, JZ, 2012. Fungal planet description sheets: 107-127. Persoonia 28: 138 - 182, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3767/003158512X652633" title="Fungal planet description sheets: 107 - 127." url="https://doi.org/10.3767/003158512X652633" volume="28" year="2012">Crous et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3390/f10111016" author="Jiang, N" journalOrPublisher="Forests" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" pagination="1 - 1016" refId="B18" refString="Jiang, N, Tian, CM, 2019. An emerging pathogen from rotted chestnut in China: Gnomoniopsis daii sp. nov. Forests 10: 1 - 1016, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3390/f10111016" title="An emerging pathogen from rotted chestnut in China: Gnomoniopsis daii sp. nov." url="https://doi.org/10.3390/f10111016" volume="10" year="2019">Jiang and Tian 2019</bibRefCitation>
). However, we can distinguish them easily by the phylogram of ITS, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">tef1</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">tub2</emphasis>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Consensus tree resulting from a RAxML analysis of combined ITS, tef 1 and tub 2 sequence alignment for species of Gnomoniopsis. The scale bar represents the expected number of changes per site." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.67.51133.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/409834" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">2</figureCitation>
). In addition, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. M. Tian &amp; N. Jiang" authorityYear="2020" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Gnomoniaceae" genus="Gnomoniopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Gnomoniopsis chinensis" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="chinensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Gnomoniopsis chinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. daii" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="daii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">G. daii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
inhabit the Chinese chestnut (
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Castanea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Castanea mollissima" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mollissima">
